    "• Evidence P(X 1∶T): The total probability of observing the data X 1∶T, which serves as a normalizing factor, ensuring that posterior probabilities sum to 1.In this context, the posterior probability P(E|X 1∶T) indicates the updated probability of an extreme event, conditioned on the observed rainfall data up to time T. Model complexity and over-fittingDNNs are complex and may overfit normal patterns while missing on extreme values.",
    "DNNs can easily memorize frequent patterns, but they might not learn the nuanced characteristics of rare events due to their complexity and the imbalance in data representation.",
    "This results in an output that performs well on common patterns and on extreme values performance is below average.",
    "Consider a DNN with parameters.",
    "The loss function L() minimized during training can be expressed as in eqaution 7:(6) P(E|X 1∶T) = P(X 1∶T |E)P(E) P(X 1∶T)Where, is a loss for a single instance."
